{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17568976","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17568976"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T00:23:47+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T00:23:47+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"21535"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"21535","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/21535"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.03,0.26,0.19,0.33,0.2]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"14404"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"115066"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"14404","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/14404"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"21535"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"97074"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"28"},{"type":"tags","id":"31"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"1051"},{"type":"tags","id":"1052"},{"type":"tags","id":"4979"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"5132"},{"type":"tags","id":"9121"},{"type":"tags","id":"11639"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"},{"type":"tags","id":"12921"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"36142"},{"type":"contributions","id":"40565"},{"type":"contributions","id":"43752"},{"type":"contributions","id":"48462"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"115066","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/115066"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 74-year-old woman is admitted to a small GP-led community hospital for symptom management. She is undergoing home-based palliative care for metastatic lung cancer. Over the past three days, she has experienced persistent nausea and occasional vomiting every four to six hours. She has not opened her bowels for the past three days. She describes constant nausea that is aggravated by movement and smells and is only partially relieved by intermittent sublingual ondansetron wafers given by ambulance staff during transfer. Her medical history includes total colectomy, type 2 diabetes and stage 4 chronic kidney disease. Current medications comprise a continuous subcutaneous morphine infusion, breakthrough subcutaneous fentanyl, transdermal fentanyl for background pain, paracetamol, subcutaneous midazolam at night for agitation and a laxative regimen. Because of oral candidiasis and profound fatigue, she cannot swallow tablets, and she has declined a nasogastric tube.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she appears fatigued but alert. Her pulse rate is 92/min, blood pressure 108/64 mmHg, respiratory rate 18/min, SpO2 96% on room air, and temperature 36.9\u00b0C. Abdominal examination shows mild distension with high-pitched bowel sounds in the lower quadrants.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following medications administered subcutaneously is most appropriate to relieve her nausea?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Midazolam","Ondansetron","Haloperidol","Metoclopramide","Domperidone"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHaloperidol\u003C/strong\u003E is the preferred subcutaneous antiemetic in this case, given the symptoms and signs suggestive of bowel obstruction. At low doses, it blocks dopaminergic receptors, adds minimal extra sedation, has little anticholinergic burden and can be given once daily or by continuous infusion, fitting this patient\u0027s needs.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMetoclopramide\u003C/strong\u003E and domperidone are dopamine receptor blockers and are available systemically, but their prokinetic action may worsen pain associated with bowel obstruction. In addition, cumulative dosing increases extrapyramidal risk, particularly with metoclopramide; they are better suited to nausea dominated by gastric stasis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EOndansetron\u003C/strong\u003E targets serotonin receptors and can be delivered parenterally, yet it is mainly used for chemotherapy-induced or visceral nausea and is constipating\u2014undesirable in a patient receiving high-dose opioids with limited bowel function.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMidazolam\u003C/strong\u003E is a benzodiazepine that may reduce anxiety or anticipatory nausea but does not act on emetic pathways and produces significant sedation, contrary to the aim of maintaining alertness.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDomperidone\u003C/strong\u003E is a peripheral dopamine antagonist that, like metoclopramide, has prokinetic properties that could worsen pain in bowel obstruction. Additionally, domperidone cannot be administered subcutaneously, making it an inappropriate choice for this patient who cannot take oral medications and has declined nasogastric tube placement.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Choice of antiemetic in palliative care is guided by presumed receptor involvement, sedative load and feasible routes of administration.","Subcutaneous haloperidol is an option for nausea and vomiting associated with bowel obstruction in the palliative care setting.","Prokinetic drugs, including metoclopramide, may worsen pain associated with bowel obstruction."],"references":["eTherapeutic Guidelines. Nausea and vomiting in palliative care [Internet]. Melbourne (AU): Therapeutic Guidelines Ltd; 2024. Available at: https://www.tg.org.au/etgcomplete","Currow DC, Agar MR, Phillips JL. Palliative management of nausea and vomiting in advanced cancer. Aust J Gen Pract [Internet]. 2024 Nov;(Supplement):S1\u2013S9. Available at: https://www1.racgp.org.au/ajgp/2024/supplement-november/palliative-management-of-nausea-and-vomiting-in-ad","NSW Clinical Excellence Commission. Management of nausea and/or vomiting in the last days of life \u2013 adult [Internet]. Sydney: NSW Health; 2017. Available at: https://www.cec.health.nsw.gov.au/__data/assets/pdf_file/0007/359341/LDOL-Flowchart-NAUSEA-and-VOMITING-2017.pdf"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"97074"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"21535"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"97074","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/97074"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-09-22T09:02:02+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-09-22T09:03:35+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"14404"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"115066"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"25","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/25"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc68\u200d\ud83d\udc69\u200d\ud83d\udc66","name":"General Practice","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"6"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"28","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/28"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc95","name":"Palliative Care","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"31","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/31"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83c\udf97","name":"Oncology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:45+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGr